## Output structure (MANDATORY)

```markdown
# Plan — <title>

## 1. Task DAG (mermaid)

\`\`\`mermaid
graph TD
    T1[task 1: ...] --> T3[task 3: ...]
    T2[task 2: ...] --> T3
    T3 --> T4
\`\`\`

Every node ID (T1, T2, ...) is referenced in §2 with concrete description.

## 2. Task descriptions

For each Tn:
- Owner (agent profile: planner | architect | coder | reviewer | tester)
- Inputs (artifact refs from upstream)
- Output (artifact ref this task produces)
- Acceptance criteria (1 sentence each, verifiable)

## 3. Risk register (LCO-style)

| ID | Risk | Likelihood | Impact | Mitigation | Escalate if... |
|----|------|-----------|--------|------------|----------------|

Each risk gets an ID (R1, R2, ...) referenced by downstream stages.

## 4. Decisions deferred to architecture

Things you intentionally did NOT decide in plan because architecture should
have the full context. Be explicit so architecture can't claim you punted
silently.

- D1: <decision> — defer to architecture because <reason>

## 5. LCO anchor commitment

Mark the explicit go/no-go statement:
- ✅ **GO**: the task DAG is sufficient to deliver the success criteria from
  intake, given the risks above.
- ❌ **NO-GO**: <reason> — escalate to user before architecture stage.

If you can't honestly commit to GO, output NO-GO with a specific reason.
Architecture will not run if plan ends NO-GO.

## 6. Design-stage handoff (one paragraph)

What architecture must investigate first; which intake unknowns are
blocking; which research counter-evidence to revisit.
```

## Hard limits

- ≤ 1500 words (counted)
- DAG must have ≥ 2 nodes (or it's not a DAG — flag as "too small for AISEP,
  do directly")
- Every risk MUST have a likelihood + impact + mitigation; no "TBD" allowed
- Commitment line (GO / NO-GO) is mandatory
